snippet.textDisplay: Hi  Kyle, you might want to check the air pressure in rear tires to make sure they are the same before you start making any adjustments.  I one is lower than the other is may contribute to difference in ride heights.  I have experienced this in the past when my street machine did a wheelie.  Pulled to the right because one tire was 7 pounds lower than the other.  You might think about wheelie bars too they make a big difference in that they keep the front end on the ground.  wheelies might look cool, but if you want fast 1/4 mile times keeping the front on the ground is where its at.  I bet Tod could make you a set just by looking at pictures.

snippet.textDisplay:
May not be the strut top mounts, as that small slip isn't enough for that amount of camber change, but the pinch bolts that attach the hub housings to the struts - they're used for camber adjustment and a good whack like that could have moved them slightly - maybe even kinked them a little. [edit, NM, got to that bit]


If you haven't already got them, pick up some corner weight scales - you'll be able to set the pre-loads (spring seats) to maximise traction.

With RWD, and a car that's so light on the front end, I'd start by doing the side-to-side weight distribution with the driver, fluids, etc. Put plates under the rears and jack the front up under the middle of the crossmember, than move what you can to even out the rear loadings and check the ride heights and alignments are equal. Then drop it onto the fronts as well and equalise the weights across the axles and check the front alignments.
Best traction is when the tyres are evenly loaded, side to side, and have the same load ACROSS the tyre tread. That also means ZERO camber on launch - I noticed some of the FWD cars are running some camber at that point and it should be dialled out.


Anyway, when are the wheelie bars going on ;-)

snippet.textDisplay: I know you said no wheelie bars yet But I think you would find that it would be much easier to tune the suspension with them on and launching the car exactly as you did causing the wheel stand. You cant really tune the suspension correctly changing how you run the car, kinda need to decide on how you really plan to run the car at all events and if wheelie bars are keeping you out of some classes or events you need to remember wheelie bars are removable if not needed. Good luck with everything, love your videos especially when you race at home, Bandimere was my home track for years good memories there.
